SIMPLE: pliant
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pliant
<hw>Pli"ant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>pliant</ets>,
p. pr. of <ets>plier</ets> to bend. See <er>Ply</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Capable of plying or bending;
readily yielding to force or pressure without breaking; flexible;
pliable; lithe; limber; plastic; <as>as, a <ex>pliant</ex> thread;
<ex>pliant</ex> wax</as>. Also used figuratively: Easily influenced for
good or evil; tractable; <as>as, a <ex>pliant</ex> heart</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The will was then ductile and <qex>pliant</qex> to right
reason.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Favorable to pliancy.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>pliant</xex> hour.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> --
<wordforms><wf>Pli"ant*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Pli"ant*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plica</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
